definition.value: A tendency within the broader American Patriot movement that emphasizes Christian nationalism. Like the larger movement, it promotes a revisionist interpretation of American history in which the federal government has turned against the ideas of liberty and natural rights expressed in the American Revolution.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from conservatism.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from paleoconservatism.

A tradition in right-wing politics; the reactionary stance opposes policies for the social transformation of society, whereas conservatives seek to preserve the socio-economic structure and order that exists in the present. In popular usage, reactionary refers to a strongly traditionalist conservative political perspective of the person who is opposed to social, political, and economic change.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from reactionism.

An anti-democratic, anti-egalitarian, reactionary philosophy. In 2007 and 2008, Curtis Yarvin, writing under the pen name Mencius Moldbug, articulated what would develop into Dark Enlightenment thinking. Yarvin's theories were elaborated and expanded by Nick Land, who first coined the term Dark Enlightenment in his essay of the same name. The term "Dark Enlightenment" is a reaction to the Age of Enlightenment.
Politics which are far-right and white nationalist in nature, originating in the United States during the early 2010s before establishing a presence in other countries and declining after 2017.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from nationalism.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from fascism.

Any of a series of loosely connected far-right, white nationalist movements. A largely online phenomenon, the alt-right originated in the United States during the early 2010s before establishing a presence in other countries and declining after 2017. The term is ill-defined, having been used in different ways by alt-right members, media commentators, and academics.
Any of various religious movements which emphasize some form of nationalism.
Any of various Christian movements which emphasize some form of nationalism.
Any of various Evangelical religions and churches primarily located, formed within, or heavily associated with, North America.
A medical facility that provides abortions. Such clinics may be public medical centers, private medical practices or nonprofit organizations such as Planned Parenthood.
Socio-political movement which embraces and promotes the ideology of conservatism within a LGBTQ context.
Any of various movements which derive their beliefs from social conservatism.
A socially conservative movement which advocates against abortion.
A socially conservative movement which advocates against contraception.
A socially conservative movement which advocates against pornography.
A form of second-wave feminism which is opposed to pornography, staking out the position that pornography was inherently exploitative toward women.
A subgenre of pornography involving the description or depiction of rape.
A socially conservative movement which advocates against feminism.
Any of various rooms used in for sexual purposes or in relationship to sex.
A room (or space) which is designed specifically for sexual purposes, oftentimes including BDSM-related equipment.

A type of psychotherapy developed by American psychiatrist Aaron T. Beck. CT is one therapeutic approach within the larger group of cognitive and behavioral therapies and was first expounded by Beck in the 1960s. Cognitive therapy is based on the cognitive model, which states that thoughts, feelings and behavior are all connected, and that individuals can move toward overcoming difficulties and meeting their goals by identifying and changing unhelpful or inaccurate thinking, problematic behavior, and distressing emotional responses. This involves the individual working with the therapist to develop skills for testing and changing beliefs, identifying distorted thinking, relating to others in different ways, and changing behaviors.

The distribution of health-related services and information via electronic information and telecommunication technologies. It allows long-distance patient and clinician contact, care, advice, reminders, education, intervention, monitoring, and remote admissions
Telehealth based around LGBTQIA+ health services.
Penetration of the anus using a piece of skinned ginger root.
The insertion of an object or objects into the vagina as part of sexual behavior.
The insertion of a body part or other object into the urethra as part of sexual behavior.
Penetration of the vagina using a piece of skinned ginger root.
The insertion of an object or objects into a body part or parts as part of sexual behavior.

The practice of inserting a piece of skinned ginger root into the human anus or the vagina in order to generate an acute burning sensation. Historically this was a method of punishment, but it has since been adopted as a practice of BDSM.
A worldwide community of fans of literary works.
A fandom based on the philosophy espoused in John Norman's long-running sword and planet novel series Chronicles of Counter-Earth.

Norman's non-fictional sex manual Imaginative Sex presents a series of elaborate fantasy scenarios to be acted out in isolated scenes. He also recommends the use of symbolic substitutes, such as the sound of claps as a substitute for whippings and other physical punishments. Pat Califia asserts that Norman was critical of the psychological and physical harm that non-stop BDSM slavery and corporal punishment might inflict. However, such views of Norman are not part of the Gorean canon and debate on Gorean practices' relationship to BDSM, focusing on aspects such as Total Power Exchange and further complicated by the community's diverse nature, continue. BDSM writer Michael Makai nevertheless asserts that Gorean fiction may be found responsible for shaping or otherwise popularizing many of today's established BDSM protocols and tenets.
The practice of including actual (or simulated) firearms into a scene.
Any of a class of activities meant to impart physical sensations upon a partner, as opposed to mental forms of erotic play such as power exchange or sexual roleplaying.

A human sexual practice in which one person is struck (usually repeatedly) by another person for the gratification of either or both parties which may or may not be sexual in nature. It is considered a form of BDSM.
Any of various styles of bondage which originated in Japan, or are heavily associated with Japan.

A Japanese term meaning "tight binding", referring to a style of bondage or BDSM which involves tying a person up using simple yet visually intricate patterns, usually with several pieces of thin rope (often jute, hemp or linen and generally around 6 mm (0.24 in) in diameter, but sometimes as small as 4 mm (0.16 in), and between 78 m (2326 ft) long.
Note that this term does not convey the meaning of sexual bondage outside SM circles.
A Japanese term meaning "the beauty of tight binding".
A Japanese word that broadly means "binding" or "tying" in most contexts, but is used in BDSM to refer to this style of decorative bondage.
Note that this term does not convey the meaning of sexual bondage outside SM circles.
Any of various forms of terrorism against abortion clinics, providers, and/or services, as well as terrorism against pro-choice (pro-abortion) advocates and activists.
A form of terrorism in which victims "within a country are targeted by a perpetrator with the same citizenship" as the victims.

A form of terrorism motivated by nationalism. Nationalist terrorists seek to form self-determination in some form, which may range from gaining greater autonomy to establishing a completely independent, sovereign state (separatism). Nationalist terrorists often oppose what they consider to be occupying, imperial, or otherwise illegitimate powers.
Terrorism related to white supremacy, a type of radical ideology which espouses that seeks to develop and maintain a white national identity.

The use of the Internet to conduct violent acts that result in, or threaten, the loss of life or significant bodily harm, in order to achieve political or ideological gains through threat or intimidation.

A form of terrorism that, unlike other forms such as right-wing, left-wing and religious terrorism, tend to focus on a few or only one specific issue rather than on more widespread political, religious or other social change.
Forms of political violence organized by type.
Forms of political violence organized by the issue or issues which spurred or influenced it.
